<LP>
   PHILIPS PLANS to cut 10,000 jobs, about 3.5% of its work
force, and expects a loss this year of about $1 billion. But
newly installed Chairman Jan Timmer said the Dutch
electronics giant won't give up on its troubled computer and
semiconductor operations. Philips's share price tumbled on
the announcement. Analysts criticized the job cuts as too
small.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Ingersoll II is relinquishing his debt-burdened U.S.
publishing empire to partner Warburg Pincus. In exchange,
Ingersoll will get Warburg's 50% interest in a publisher of
English and Irish newspapers.
   ---
   General Instrument received a $1.42 billion buy-out bid
from Forstmann Little, which has dominated the buy-out field
this year. General Instrument's stock surged on the news, and
competing bids for the maker of cable-TV gear could
materialize.
   ---
   Saks's trading profit totaled $26.4 million in 1990's
first half, 20% less than new owner Investcorp forecast when
it bid for the retailer. The firm plans to slash Saks's
capital spending.
   ---
   Lotus sued Borland, saying Borland's Quattro software
violates the copyright of Lotus's 1-2-3 spreadsheet program.
The suit follows Lotus's victory last week in a similar case.
   ---
   Coca-Cola named its top person in Europe, M. Douglas
Ivester, to head the Coca-Cola USA unit, fueling speculation
that he is the front-runner to succeed the parent firm's
president.
   ---
   Manufacturers showed more signs of emerging from their
long slump, according to purchasing managers, whose index of
indicators rose in June. Separately, construction spending
slipped 0.4% in May, its second drop in a row, the government
said.
   ---
   Ratners Group of Britain offered to acquire Kay Jewelers
in a stock swap. The U.S. company's board unanimously
approved the proposed deal, but the transaction could be held
up by holders of Kay's junk bonds.
   ---
   The dollar declined, continuing a pattern that some
traders think may persist. Stocks gained and bonds held even
in thin trading. The Dow Jones industrials rose 18.57 points.
   ---
   Foreign holdings in the U.S. exceeded U.S. holdings abroad
last year by $663.75 billion, nearly 25% more than the year
before, but the government said the number was inaccurate.
   ---
   Soybean prices rallied wildly amid forecasts of intense
heat in the Midwest and the Mississippi Delta.
   ---
   Southland disclosed details of its new debt exchange
offer. Bondholders reacted with cautious optimism. The plan
includes a reverse stock split.
   ---
   Thrift regulators eased temporarily new restrictions on
the size of S&amp;L loans to a single borrower.
   ---
   US Sprint formed a joint venture with the Soviet
government to provide high-speed data communications services
in the U.S.S.R., beginning as early as this year's fourth
quarter.
   ---
